,'2015-09-21 16:27:15','2015-09-21 10:42:15','It was my search for the elusive Maoist guerrillas which first brought me to Nepal in 2001. &nbsp; \n\nWeeks after landing in Kathmandu I received a phone call asking me to be at my hotel in half an hour. On returning to Durbar Square, I found a small boy waiting, all of 12 years perhaps. He spoke no English but bade me go with him. We bought bus-tickets and alighted twenty-seven hours later in Surkhet, where, after showing me a hotel, he simply turned and walked off. The following morning, a cadre arrived. With my gear slung, we walked down the main street under inquisitive eyes until buildings gave way to sloping contours and hills swallowed us.\\nWe continued our walk after a night in a hill-station, turning a bend after some hours to be greeted by a dozen Maoist guerrillas with garlands and red tikka, rifles held high to create a tunnel through which we walked.\\nFrom the roof of a dilapidated building I addressed the assembled group as requested before marching together for Dailekh.&nbsp; \n\nA week or so later, my first morning back in Kathmandu, chaotic scenes woke me. Outside my window unruly crowds mobbed newspaper vendors. I rushed down and, after a brief and futile attempt to queue as my English upbringing demanded, I fought hand and fist for a paper. &nbsp; \n\n&quot;What does it say?&quot; I asked my hotel manager.<p>&nbsp;</p>\n&quot;It appears that the Royal Family has been massacred.&quot;<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\nThe mediaeval scenes I was privileged to have witnessed in the days that followed imbued me with a deep-rooted sense of responsibility to the Nepali people. I determined that I would return whenever I could to document their unfolding struggle.<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\nHere, exhibited for the first time in Nepal are my photographs.A work, dedicated to a brave, generous and long-suffering people.\n\nFrom the roof of a dilapidated building I addressed the assembled group as requested before marching together for Dailekh.<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\nA week or so later, my first morning back in Kathmandu, chaotic scenes woke me. Outside my window unruly crowds mobbed newspaper vendors. I rushed down and, after a brief and futile attempt to queue as my English upbringing demanded, I fought hand and fist for a paper.<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n\"What does it say?\" I asked my hotel manager.\n\"It appears that the Royal Family has been massacred.\"\nThe mediaeval scenes I was privileged to have witnessed in the days that followed imbued me with a deep-rooted sense of responsibility to the Nepali people. I determined that I would return whenever I could to document their unfolding struggle.\nHere, exhibited for the first time in Nepal are my photographs.\n</span>\n\n<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;It was my search for the elusive Maoist guerrillas which first brought me to Nepal in 2001.\\nWeeks after landing in Kathmandu I received a phone call asking me to be at my hotel in half an hour. \\nOn returning to Durbar Square, I found a small boy waiting, all of 12 years perhaps. He spoke no English but bade me go with him. We bought bus-tickets and alighted twenty-seven hours later in Surkhet, where, after showing me a hotel, he simply turned and walked off. \\nThe following morning, a cadre arrived. With my gear slung, we walked down the main street under inquisitive eyes until buildings gave way to sloping contours and hills swallowed us.\\nWe continued our walk after a night in a hill-station, turning a bend after some hours to be greeted by a dozen Maoist guerrillas with garlands and red tikka, rifles held high to create a tunnel through which we walked.\\nFrom the roof of a dilapidated building I addressed the assembled group as requested before marching together for Dailekh.\\nA week or so later, my first morning back in Kathmandu, chaotic scenes woke me. Outside my window unruly crowds mobbed newspaper vendors. I rushed down and, after a brief and futile attempt to queue as my English upbring