iance Franaise in Kathmandu, Banshi Ghat Marga, Teku Road, Tripureshwor\nTime: 2 pm\nLanguage: English\nNo. of Participants: 12 max\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>APPLICATION REQUIREMENTS</strong></span>\nParticipants should be eager to learn and share\n- Participants should have a basic technical base in photography and should be comfortable shooting on manual function with a DSLR camera.\n- Participants should be able to commit to four full days. Although the workshop hours are only 9-2, participants are expected to shoot for the rest of the days.\n- Female photographers are highly encouraged to apply.\n- Participation fee is Rs. 4,000 / $40\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>HOW TO APPLY\n- </strong></span>To apply, please fill in this <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B1XMdR4hZTgmdFV2MVRSQzRDb1k/view?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\">application form</a>and email it to <a href=\"mailto:mail@photoktm.com\">mail@photoktm.com </a>with the subject: Photographing the Everyday\n- Send us 10 of your best photos [800 pixels on the longest side].\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">DEADLINE:</span> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">10 October</span>\n</strong>','PHOTOGRAPHING THE EVERYDAY','','inherit','closed','closed','','241-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-22 20:45:33','2015-09-22 15:00:33','',241,'http://localhost/pktm-event/index.php/2015/09/22/241-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(243,4,'2015-09-22 09:25:28','2015-09-22 03:40:28','This 4 day seminar will explore practical and conceptual approaches of use to those generating critical commentaries about photography. Its scope will be global, but its particular focus will be South Asian. The seminars will introduce participants to current understandings of the history of photography and also convey a detailed narrative of photographys development within South Asia. The seminars also aim to develop awareness about different styles of writing about photography and to help participants advance their own techniques through practical assignments. The workshop will explore a range of different approaches to writing photography with an intention to clarify issues of style, genre, and context so that seminar participants can define and finesse their own interests and ways of writing.\r\n\r\nIt will explore a global history of photography with an aim to establish what as critics and writers, we need to know about the changing nature of apparatus. We will pay particular attention to early techniques, the development of smaller and faster apparatus, and the advent of the digital. We will consider whether circulation has displaced the image as such. We will also consider a range of theoretical approaches to photography that are important to us as writers: what might be our position on photographys indexicality, on the way in which images are determined by their contexts, and our view of recent claims that photography offers a citizenship in advance of conventional political rights?\r\nIt will also explore in some detail the history of photography in South Asia tracing its career from the first Daguerreotypes in Calcutta in 1840 through to Rashid Ranas pixelated images, and digital platforms such as the Indian Memory Project, photo.circle and Nepal Picture Library. We will also ask how this regional history can be inserted in the mainstream of a global narrative rather than simply added as a footnote.\r\n\r\nAnd it will involve a collective discussion of texts that participants have been working on throughout the seminar. This will be a constructive collective crit in which we will all learn from one anothers individual approaches and perspectives.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>WORKSHOP DETAILS</strong></span>\r\nDate: November 2-5, 2015\r\nVenue: Yala Maya Kendra, Patan Dhoka\r\nTime: 9 am - 2 pm\r\nLanguage: English\r\nNo. of Participants: 12 max\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">APPLICATION REQUIREMENTS:</span></strong>\r\nThe workshop is designed for writers who are interested in writing about photography and learn its history.\r\n\r\nApart from the <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1XMdR4hZTgmTVlTdUZIa0ZWQjg\" target=\"_blank\">Application form</a>, interested participants should also send their updated CV and one writing sample of 800-2500 words to <a href=\"mailto:mail@photoktm.com\">mail@photoktm.com </a>with the subject: Writing Photography\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">WORKSHOP FEE:</span></strong> Rs. 4,000 / $40\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>DEADLINE:</strong></span> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>10 October</strong></span>','WRITING PHOTOGRAPHY','','publish','closed','closed','','engaging-with-photography-through-text','','','2015-09-23 13:58:17','2015-09-23 08:13:17','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=exhibition&#038;p=243',0,'exhibition','',0),(244,4,'2015-09-22 12:31:28','2015-09-22 06:46:28','Visual media have been used to advocate for positive social change since the invention of photography and the moving image. With visual communication increasing exponentially via the digital democratization of production and publication, it is more important than ever than individuals and organizations working for social justice understand the potential impact images can have and incorporate them effectively in their work.\r\n\r\nThis two-day workshop is aimed at both visual practitioners and communication/ campaign staff in social justice organizations. The workshop will look at:\r\n\r\n- Past &amp; Current practice - by exploring the trajectory of visual media for social change we will explore a range of - issues and approaches relevant to anyone wishing to use images in their work on social justice. This will include looking at a range of visual approaches and best practice.\r\n- Ethics - We will explore issues of representation, collaborative methodologies, security and truth.\r\n- Impact - Here we explore how to best prepare a communication strategy, from knowing the issue, working with communities / civil society, to audiences / dissemination.\r\n- Practical exercises and discussion groups - the workshop will have a number of practical exercises and discussion groups to allow participants to explore the issues covered.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>WORKSHOP DETAILS</strong></span>\r\nDate: 5-6 November 2015\r\nVenue: Yala Maya Kendra, Patan Dhoka\r\nTime: 2 pm\r\nLanguage: English\r\nNo. of Participants: 15 max\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>APPLICATION REQUIREMENTS</strong></span>\r\nThe workshop is designed for people working in communication and outreach department of various I/NGOs like communication officers, media officers and outreach officers as well as for photographers interested in getting involved in social justice campaigns.\r\n\r\nOn top of <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1XMdR4hZTgmYTNMOVF4dVFMalU\" target=\"_blank\">thisApplication form</a>, interested participants are also required to send in their updated CV to <a href=\"mailto:mail@photoktm.com\">mail@photoktm.com</a> with the subject: Using Visual Media in Social Justice\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>WORKSHOP FEE:</strong></span> Rs. 10,000 / $100 (three scholarship positions available, please add a paragraph in your app form requesting for scholarship and explaining why)\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">DEADLINE:</span> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">10 October 2015</span></strong>','USING VISUAL MEDIA FOR SOCIAL JUSTICE CAMPAIGNS','','publish','closed','closed','','using-visual-media-for-social-justice-campaigns','','','2015-09-23 12:13:25','2015-09-23 06:28:25','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=exhibition&#038;p=244',0,'exhibition','',0),(245,4,'2015-09-22 12:34:39','2015-09-22 06:49:39','A hands-on workshop where you will see how to turn your phone camera into a professional tool. Whether you have Android, Windows or iPhone, your subject, composition, light and timing are key to success. Apps are many, some free, some cost, but creating your own style and building a portfolio based on that style will improve the quality of your work. We will look at great apps, simple filters, aspect ratios and output for print or online publishing. From landscape, still life and portrait you will discover how to maximise the capacity of your device to make great photographs.\r\n\r\nApplicants should be familiar with the camera on their device including turning flash on or off. They should have at least 2GB memory available and more is better. They should be familiar with downloading apps, and managing their camera roll or photo library. Applicants should be familiar with the camera on their device including turning flash on or off. They should have at least 2GB memory available and more is better. They should be familiar with downloading apps, and managing their camera roll or photo library.','MOBILE MAGIC - GREAT PHOTOS FROM SMALL DEVICES','','publish','closed','closed','','mobile-magic-great-photographs-from-small-devices','','','2015-09-22 15:31:33','2015-09-22 09:46:33','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=exhibition&#038;p=245',0,'exhibition','',0),(246,4,'2015-09-22 17:46:47','2015-09-22 12:01:47','This 4 day seminar will explore practical and conceptual approaches of use to those generating critical commentaries about photography. Its scope will be global, but its particular focus will be South Asian. The seminars will introduce participants to current understandings of the history of photography and also convey a detailed narrative of photographys development within South Asia. The seminars also aim to develop awareness about different styles of writing about photography and to help participants advance their own techniques through practical assignments. The workshop will explore a range of different approaches to writing photography with an intention to clarify issues of style, genre, and context so that seminar participants can define and finesse their own interests and ways of writing.\n\nIt will explore a global history of photography with an aim to establish what as critics and writers, we need to know about the changing nature of apparatus. We will pay particular attention to early techniques, the development of smaller and faster apparatus, and the advent of the digital. We will consider whether circulation has displaced the image as such. We will also consider a range of theoretical approaches to photography that are important to us as writers: what might be our position on photographys indexicality, on the way in which images are determined by their contexts, and our view of recent claims that photography offers a citizenship in advance of conventional political rights?\nIt will also explore in some detail the history of photography in South Asia tracing its career from the first Daguerreotypes in Calcutta in 1840 through to Rashid Ranas pixelated images, and digital platforms such as the Indian Memory Project, photo.circle and Nepal Picture Library. We will also ask how this regional history can be inserted in the mainstream of a global narrative rather than simply added as a footnote.\n\nAnd it will involve a collective discussion of texts that participants have been working on throughout the seminar. This will be a constructive collective crit in which we will all learn from one anothers individual approaches and perspectives.\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>WORKSHOP DETAILS</strong></span>\nDate: November 2-5, 2015\nVenue: Yala Maya Kendra, Patan\nTime: 9 am - 2 pm\nLanguage: English\nNo. of Particpants: 12 max\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">APPLICATION REQUIREMENTS:</span></strong>\nThe workshop is designed for writers who are interested in writing about photography and learn its history.\nApart from the <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1XMdR4hZTgmTVlTdUZIa0ZWQjg\" target=\"_blank\">Application form</a>, interested participants should also send their updated CV and one writing sample of 800-2500 words to mail@photoktm.com with the subject: Writing Photography\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">WORKSHOP FEE:</span></strong> Rs. 4000 (inclusive of VAT)\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>DEADLINE:</strong></span> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>10 October</strong></span>','WRITING PHOTOGRAPHY','','inherit','closed','closed','','243-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-22 17:46:47','2015-09-22 12:01:47','',243,'http://localhost/pktm-event/index.php/2015/09/22/243-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(247,1,'2015-09-22 13:50:26','2015-09-22 08:05:26','<div class=\"story-intro\"><strong>WOOLWORTHS has admitted it got it wrong by slashing staff hours in a bid to cut costs, resulting in poorly stocked shelves and dismal service, but the supermarket giant claims customers are beginning to see the results of a massive turnaround plan.</strong>\n\n</div>\nDave Chambers, the new director of Woolworths supermarkets who replaced Tjeerd Jegen in February, <a href=\"http://www.afr.com/business/woolworths-to-spend-65m-fixing-stores-20150917-gjold1\">told the <i>Australian Financial Review</i> he was shocked by what he saw</a> when he first joined the company, from long queues to trolleys in disrepair.\n\nCustomers were saying service wasnt good enough and availability wasnt good enough, Mr Chambers told the <i>AFR</i>.\n\nBut the retailer says its making progress as it rolls out $65 million worth of upgrades to its stores, and now receives daily feedback as part of its voice of the customer surveys to quickly address issues.\n\nWe are starting to do better on <a href=\"http://www.news.com.au/finance/business/why-woolies-is-a-basket-case/story-fnkgdftz-1227507127981\">trolley and baskets and staff attitude</a>, he said. Fruit and vegetables and queue time and out-of-stocks are the three areas we have the most opportunity in.\n\nIn its <a href=\"http://www.woolworthslimited.com.au/icms_docs/182362_FY15_Analyst_Presentation.pdf\">full-year results presentation</a> last month  one of its worst in nearly 20 years as a public company  Woolworths announced it had already reinvested 56,000 staff hours per week across its 950 stores. The company says it now wants to add an extra 63,000 hours in the coming year.\n\nThe real-time feedback we receive from thousands of Woolworths customers each month means we know what store improvements are working and highlights where we can make more, a Woolworths spokesman told news.com.au.\n\nFor instance we regularly receive positive feedback around our in-store teams friendly interaction with customers on the shop floor.\n\nCustomers also tell us that they value good quality trolleys to help them get around the store. This has meant we are now investing in new trolley fleets in hundreds of our supermarkets.\n\nWith sales volumes relatively static in supermarkets  shoppers tend to be the same people buying the same things every week  cutting prices wreaks havoc with profit margins.','First News Piece Copy','','inherit','closed','closed','','232-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-22 13:50:26','2015-09-22 08:05:26','',232,'http://localhost/pktm-event/index.php/2015/09/22/232-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(248,4,'2015-09-22 14:00:13','2015-09-22 08:15:13','\"As if there still weren\'t enough of reality, of that awful reality\" Henri Michaux\r\n\r\nIts been about twenty years now. Why do I come back endlessly? As an answer, I was long able to formulate nothing but beginnings of speeches about the youth, its rather sorry energy, its smiling resignation I falter, unable to formulate anything consistent nor convincing. Disorder. Tis why lies in a nebulous angle of my mind.\r\n\r\nElusive but dense.\r\n\r\nBut if I would hold back for a moment on this word, disorder, and question it, I would notice a certain match between my own disorder and the one that controls these towns and villages where I keep coming back, season after season. A certain match with this territory that does not know the void and where auspicious stones have been erected in the few places that were left virgin by the secular hustle: this territory that appeases me.\r\n\r\nDescending from the airport each time I return, shaken up by the traffic jam and the insane driving, suffocated by the racket, the lead and the nitrates, I simply slip into a world where I already exist, soothed in the shadow of its chaos. A world in which I feel recognised. A glance, a dog, a twisted line of ragged walls, a pond, a ladybird on the half-open window of the car, a butchers shop on the pavement, the spasms of a bus, the light burn of the tea on the lips I receive them as a solace. Death, violence, fever, the air drizzling with dust and heavy metals, the overload of the space: nothing offends me. I am in the right place. A place that is searching for balance, a balance between order and disorder.\r\n\r\nOn that basis, lingering on what sits just next to the facts, or under them, or behind them, or who knows where else in their vicinity, drifting away in their faint lights, it would perhaps be possible to build up the beginning of an answer to this question: why Nepal?','EVERYDAY EPIPHANIES','','publish','closed','closed','','everyday-epiphanies','','','2015-09-24 16:22:50','2015-09-24 10:37:50','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=exhibition&#038;p=248',0,'exhibition','',0),(249,4,'2015-09-22 15:14:37','2015-09-22 09:29:37','<span data-sheets-value=\"[null,2,&quot;Christopher Pinney is an anthropologist and art historian. He is currently Professor of Anthropology and Visual Culture at University College London. He has held visiting positions at the Australian National University, University of Chicago, University of Cape Town, Northwestern University, Bo\\u011fazi\\u00e7i University (Istanbul), and Jagiellonian University (Krakow). His research interests cover the art and visual culture of South Asia, with a particular focus on the history of photography and chromolithography in India. He has also worked on industrial labor and Dalit goddess possession. He gave the Panizzi Lectures at the British Library in 2006, the Ramakrisha Nataraja Lecture in 2010 (Hyderabad), the Gerbrands Memorial Lecture (Leiden) in 2014 and the M.N. Srinivas Memorial Lecture (London) in 2015. Amongst his publications are Camera Indica (1997), \\u2018Photos of the Gods\\u2019(2004),The Coming of Photography in India (2008) and (together with the photographer Suresh Punjabi) Artisan Camera: Studio Photography from Central India (2013)\\n&quot;]\" data-sheets-userformat=\"[null,null,9129,[null,0],null,null,[null,[[null,2,0,null,null,[null,2,0]],[null,0,0,3],[null,1,0,null,1]]],null,[null,[[null,2,0,null,null,[null,2,0]],[null,0,0,3],[null,1,0,null,1]]],null,0,4,0,null,null,null,10]\">Christopher Pinney is an anthropologist and art historian. He is currently Professor of Anthropology and Visual Culture at University College London. He has held visiting positions at the Australian National University, University of Chicago, University of Cape Town, Northwestern University, Boazii University (Istanbul), and Jagiellonian University (Krakow). His research interests cover the art and visual culture of South Asia, with a particular focus on the history of photography and chromolithography in India. He has also worked on industrial labor and Dalit goddess possession. He gave the Panizzi Lectures at the British Library in 2006, the Ramakrisha Nataraja Lecture in 2010 (Hyderabad), the Gerbrands Memorial Lecture (Leiden) in 2014 and the M.N. Srinivas Memorial Lecture (London) in 2015. Amongst his publications are Camera Indica (1997), Photos of the Gods(2004),The Coming of Photography in India (2008) and (together with the photographer Suresh Punjabi) Artisan Camera: Studio Photography from Central India (2013)\r\n</span>','CHRISTOPHER PINNEY','','publish','clos