 about twenty years now. Why do I come back endlessly? As an answer, I was long able to formulate nothing but beginnings of speeches about the youth, its rather sorry energy, its smiling resignation I falter, unable to formulate anything consistent nor convincing. Disorder. Tis why lies in a nebulous angle of my mind.\n\nElusive but dense.\n\nBut if I would hold back for a moment on this word, disorder, and question it, I would notice a certain match between my own disorder and the one that controls these towns and villages where I keep coming back, season after season. A certain match with this territory that does not know the void and where auspicious stones have been erected in the few places that were left virgin by the secular hustle: this territory that appeases me.\n\nDescending from the airport each time I return, shaken up by the traffic jam and the insane driving, suffocated by the racket, the lead and the nitrates, I simply slip into a world where I already exist, soothed in the shadow of its chaos. A world in which I feel recognised. A glance, a dog, a twisted line of ragged walls, a pond, a ladybird on the half-open window of the car, a butchers shop on the pavement, the spasms of a bus, the light burn of the tea on the lips I receive them as a solace. Death, violence, fever, the air drizzling with dust and heavy metals, the overload of the space: nothing offends me. I am in the right place. A place that is searching for balance, a balance between order and disorder.\n\nOn that basis, lingering on what sits just next to the facts, or under them, or behind them, or who knows where else in their vicinity, drifting away in their faint lights, it would perhaps be possible to build up the beginning of an answer to this question: why Nepal?','EVERYDAY EPIPHANIES','','inherit','closed','closed','','248-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-24 16:22:53','2015-09-24 10:37:53','',248,'http://localhost/pktm-event/index.php/2015/09/22/248-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(252,4,'2015-09-22 15:24:16','2015-09-22 09:39:16','People are central to Garys current body of work. Where earlier works explored abstract representations of man and his interaction with the environment his new work explores the people themselves. Portraits and Photo journalistic work inspire him to interact with the people he meets  either on the street on in one of his photography workshops. The iPhone, Android phone  mobile device image capture has become a driving force for him since working in developing regions of the world.','GARRY WORNELL','','publish','closed','closed','','garry-wornell','','','2015-09-23 11:34:04','2015-09-23 05:49:04','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=artist&#038;p=252',0,'artist','',0),(253,4,'2015-09-22 16:15:55','2015-09-22 10:30:55','Vincent Grby, born in 1970, has published two books on Nepal. Le nouveau Nepal ou le pari dune utopie is an essay about the Nepali revolution and was published in France by lHarmatthan. Laffaire des 16 piliers is a short detective story which takes place in Kathmandu and was published in Nepal by Vajra Publication. Vincent Greby has been studying painting as a painter assistant at the Korean art studio Sonamu in France. His work embraces painting, photography, and writing. He has exhibited his work mainly in France, Cambodia, and of course Nepal. He lives and works in Paris.\r\n\r\nThis show presents a series of portraits, all taken in Kathmandu in 2014. They are a testimony to those who arent living mainstream lives. The show is based on several months of investigation and research on the life in a raksi bar (an informal place to buy cheap booze and snacks). By means of a straight look, each portrait expresses the daily struggles with joy and fear.\r\n\r\nAs a counterpoint to these sharp encounters, some digital photographic paintings propose a breath of fresh air. Color and shape resolve the violence, singing a poem of light. This enables the audience to share common values of being human such as dignity, beauty, and hope.\r\nFurthermore, the use of flex print offers an interrogation into how to present photographic work.\r\n\r\nA similar exhibition took place in Battambang, Cambodia at the Make Maek Gallery in 2014. A series of Cambodian and Nepali streetworker portraits were hung face to face in a confrontation suggesting equitable identities.','VINCENT GREBY','','publish','closed','closed','','vincent-greby','','','2015-09-23 11:33:40','2015-09-23 05:48:40','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=artist&#038;p=253',0,'artist','',0),(254,4,'2015-09-22 16:17:39','2015-09-22 10:32:39','Lorem ipsum blablabla','*** TITLE ***','','publish','closed','closed','','title-2','','','2015-09-22 16:17:56','2015-09-22 10:32:56','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=exhibition&#038;p=254',0,'exhibition','',0),(255,4,'2015-09-23 10:18:39','2015-09-23 04:33:39','Visual media have been used to advocate for positive social change since the invention of photography and the moving image. With visual communication increasing exponentially via the digital democratization of production and publication, it is more important than ever than individuals and organizations working for social justice understand the potential impact images can have and incorporate them effectively in their work.\n\nThis two-day workshop is aimed at both visual practitioners and communication/ campaign staff in social justice organizations. The workshop will look at:\n\n- Past &amp; Current practice - by exploring the trajectory of visual media for social change we will explore a range of - issues and approaches relevant to anyone wishing to use images in their work on social justice. This will include looking at a range of visual approaches and best practice.\n- Ethics - We will explore issues of representation, collaborative methodologies, security and truth.\n- Impact - Here we explore how to best prepare a communication strategy, from knowing the issue, working with communities / civil society, to audiences / dissemination.\n- Practical exercises and discussion groups - the workshop will have a number of practical exercises and discussion groups to allow participants to explore the issues covered.\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>WORKSHOP DETAILS</strong></span>\nDate: 5-6 November 2015\nVenue: Yala Maya Kendra, Patan Dhoka\nTime: 2 pm\nLanguage: English\nNo. of Participants: 15 max\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>APPLICATION REQUIREMENTS</strong></span>\nThe workshop is designed for people working in communication and outreach department of various I/NGOs like communication officers, media officers and outreach officers as well as for photographers interested in getting involved in social justice campaigns.\n\nOn top of <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B1XMdR4hZTgmYTNMOVF4dVFMalU\" target=\"_blank\">thisApplication form</a>, interested participants are also required to send in their updated CV to <a href=\"mailto:mail@photoktm.com\">mail@photoktm.com</a> with the subject: Using Visual Media in Social Justice\n\n<span style=\"color: #e6519d;\"><strong>WORKSHOP FEE:</strong></span> Rs. 10,000 / $100 (three scholarship positions available, please add a paragraph in your app form requesting for scholarship and explaining why)\n\n<strong><span style=\"color: #e6519d;\">DEADLINE:</span> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">10 October 2015</span></strong>','USING VISUAL MEDIA FOR SOCIAL JUSTICE CAMPAIGNS','','inherit','closed','closed','','244-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-23 10:18:39','2015-09-23 04:33:39','',244,'http://localhost/pktm-event/index.php/2015/09/22/244-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(256,4,'2015-09-22 19:10:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','closed','closed','','','','','2015-09-22 19:10:24','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://localhost/pktm-event/?post_type=exhibition&p=256',0,'exhibition','',0),(257,4,'2015-09-22 21:05:57','2015-09-22 15:20:57','The first time I arrived in Susta, I had walked around 7 minutes from the river across the sandy bank to reach the village. I saw two small huts where people were selling tea and fish. I sat there talking to them for a while. The next time I went, I did not see the huts. I asked someone where the huts were. Pointing towards the river she calmly said, Somewhere there, cant be sure.\n\nSusta was once perched firmly on the west bank of the Narayani River, which has long been considered as the border between Nepal and India. However, with the river changing course due to climate change, and cutting persistently into Nepali territory, the village today finds itself on the east of the Narayani. India maintains the new course of the river as the boundary while Nepal disagrees, making Susta a contested portion of Nepal within India, surrounded on three sides by India, and on the fourth by the Narayani. It is estimated that 19,980 hectares have come under Indian encroachment thus far.\n\nThe security officials say that the Narayani breached around 500 hectares of farmland during the monsoon of 2013 in Susta. This has been occurring at an accelerated rate for almost a decade now. Now its just the farms but in 2 years time the river will start eroding the village if nothing is done, exclaims Rampyare Kurmi, a local.\n\nThere is the Save Susta Campaign (a local movement established to protest against Indian advancement into their land) on one side and also the resistance with the river, Laila Begum, a local, states, How many battles must we fight? But what are the issues that will be left to resolve if the land itself doesnt exist anymore?\n\nThis is a petition for change in Susta, resolution of the dispute between the two countries, building of retaining walls along the bank of the Narayani. This is a poem dedicated to the people of Susta, their sorrow, their grief, their determination, their resistance, their persistence, their isolation.','CHANGE OF COURSE','','inherit','closed','closed','','225-autosave-v1','','','2015-09-22 21:05:57','2015-09-22 15:20:57','',225,'http://localhost/pktm-event/index.php/2015/09/22/225-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(261,4,'2015-09-22 20:45:43','2015-09-22 15:00:43','','photographing_the_everyday','','inherit','open','closed','','photographing_the_everyday','','','2015-09-22 20:45:43','2015-09-22 15:00:43','',241,'http://localhost/pktm-event/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/photographing_the_everyday.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(262,4,'2015-09-22 20:45:59','2015-09-22 15:00:59','','writing_photography','','inherit','open','closed','','writing_photography','','','2015-09-22 20:45:59','2015-09-22 15:00:59','',243,'http://localhost/pktm-event/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/writing_photography.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(264,4,'2015-09-22 20:58:44','2015-09-22 15:13:44','','portraits_of_nepal','','inherit','open','closed','','portraits_of_nepal','','','2015-09-22 20:58:44','2015-09-22 15:13:44','',23,'http://localhost/pktm-event/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/portraits_of_nepal.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(265,4,'2015-09-22 21:02:24','2015-09-22 15:17:24','','everyday_epiphanies','','inherit','open','closed','','everyday_epiphanies','','','2015-09-22 21:02:24','2015-09-22 15:17:24','',248,'http://localhost/pktm-event/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/everyday_epiphanies.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(266,4,'2015-09-22 21:04:20','2015-09-22 15:19:20','','living_in_the_mist','','inherit','open','closed','','living_in_the_mist','','','2015-09-22 21:04:20','2015-09-22 15:19:20','',28,'http://localhost/pktm-event/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/living_in_the_mist.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(267,4,'2015-09-22 21:10:23','2015-09-22 15:25:23','','change_of_course','','inherit','open','closed','','change_of_course','','','2015-09-22 21:10:23','2015-09-22 15:25:23','',225,'http://localhost/pktm-event/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/change_of_course.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(268,4,'2015-09-22 21:15:25','2015-09-22 15:30:25',''